<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDPJ, Others Criticize Tokyo's Nuclear Stand </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDPJ, Others Criticize Tokyo's Nuclear Stand </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0806043294 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 8 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0806043294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 8 June Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] On 7 June, the Social Democratic Party of Japan 
[SDPJ] issued a statement by Chairman Tomiichi Murayama 
criticizing the government's position paper submitted to the 
International Court of Justice which expresses the view that 
"the use of nuclear weapons does not violate international law." 
The statement claims the use of nuclear arms "is a violation of 
international law, and runs counter to humanism." 
  Sakigake [Harbinger Party], Group Seiun, and Minshu no Kaze 
[Wind of Democracy] also issued an emergency statement, saying: 
"From the standpoint of the only atomic-bombed country in the 
world, Japan should actively argue the use of nuclear arms is 
highly illegal." All parties strongly demand that the 
government revise the position paper. 
  Murayama's statement, quoting the 1961 UN General Assembly 
Resolution banning the use of nuclear weapons, emphasizes: 
"Nuclear arms are weapons of indiscriminate, mass destruction 
which affect even noncombatants. The illegality of using such 
weapons is evident under existing international treaties." 
  The statement further points out: 1) Such a position is an 
affront to the sentiments of atomic bomb victims in Hiroshima 
and Nagasaki, and to the Japanese people who demand the 
extinction of nuclear weapons; and 2) a negative attitude on the 
nuclear issue will seriously jeopardize the legitimacy of 
Japanese diplomacy at a time when the DPRK's (North Korea) 
suspected development of nuclear devices is a burning issue. It 
asks the government to reconsider its position. 
  The statement issued by Sakigake and the other groups says: 
"To claim this is not illegal merely because there are no 
actual provisions on it in international law is inappropriate in 
view of ongoing efforts to gradually institutionalize 
international law to adapt to the needs of the times." 
  The "Goken Liberal no Kai [Liberals' Association for 
Safeguarding the Constitution]" in the House of Councillors also 
criticized the government's position paper for "having no 
international sense at all." It has issued a statement asking 
that the document be rescinded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

