<H3> <TI>   Government Explains Defense Contact With Indonesia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Explains Defense Contact With Indonesia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0306075594 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 3 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0306075594 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Australia says it has been incorporating human 
rights issues into its direct and indirect defense contact with 
Indonesia. The approach is outlined in an Australian Government 
response to a parliamentary report on relations with Indonesia. 
  The document said Australia's Defense Force did not provide 
training to Indonesian troops for internal security or 
counter-insurgency. 
  The statement said cooperation with Indonesian Special 
Forces 
focussed on low-level military and welfare skills, as well as 
communications operation, small arms practice, and medical 
training. 
  Foreign Minister Gareth Evans said the government shared the 
parliamentary committee's view that human rights was the most 
sensitive area of Australia's relations with Indonesia. 

</TEXT>

