<H3> <TI>   Wholesale, Retail Sales Decline 4 Percent </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wholesale, Retail Sales Decline 4 Percent </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0706081894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0726 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0706081894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, June 7 KYODO -- Wholesale and retail sales in 
Japan dropped an overall 4 percent in 1993 to 673.5 trillion 
yen, registering the first consecutive yearly decline since 
statistics of the kind began in 1953, the Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry (MITI) said Tuesday [7 June]. 
  Consumers have become more price-conscious amid uncertain 
prospects for employment and income under the recession, MITI 
said in a commerce survey. 
  Sales in the wholesale sector declined 4.1 percent and those 
in the retail sector 3.8 percent, both suffering a drop for the 
second year in a row, MITI said. 
  The annual survey report, called Japan's Commerce, is 
compiled on the basis of various commerce-related indicators. 

</TEXT>

