<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, Moscow Agree on Settling Trade Debts Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo, Moscow Agree on Settling Trade Debts Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0406051894 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 4 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFCIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0406051894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Toshihiko Kashiwa; from NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 3 Jun </F>
Evening Edition] 
  [Text] Moscow, 2 Jun -- Japan and Russia held their second 
trade and economic conference in Moscow on 2 June. In the 
meeting, the two governments agreed to make mutual efforts to 
settle at an early date the issue of Russia's delay in repaying 
debts in trade with Japan. Russia's trade debts have become a 
stumbling block to the promotion of trade between Japan and 
Russia. In the meeting, the Japanese delegates reaffirmed its 
proposal made by then Foreign Minister Hata in March that Japan 
will invite Russian leaders -- in the position of deputy prime 
minister or the equivalent -- to Japan. The two countries agreed 
to coordinate the scheduling of a visit by Russian leaders 
through diplomatic channels. 
  The meeting was attended by representatives from the 
ministries concerned of the two nations. The Japanese delegates 
were led by Deputy Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Hayashi 
while the Russian side was headed by First Deputy Minister 
Phratokov [as published] of the Foreign Economic Relations 
Ministry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

