<H3> <TI>   Canada Requests Easing of Building Standards </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Canada Requests Easing of Building Standards </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0706120394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 5 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0706120394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 4 June, the Canadian Government gave Chief 
Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai a letter requesting 
deregulation in Japan's Building Standards Law [BSL] and the 
Japanese Agricultural Standards (JAS). In a bid to urge Japan 
to increase imports of Canadian timber and other products, the 
letter has asked the Japanese Government to incorporate the 
request into a deregulation package, which will be compiled by 
the end of June. 
  Touching on the BSL, the letter claims: "Canadian-produced 
timber products are capable of satisfying fire prevention 
standards the same as those for nonwooden buildings." It 
requests the easing of building standards to enable the 
following: 1) construction of three-story wooden apartment 
houses in fire zones and semi-fire zones; and 2) construction of 
three-story wooden hotels using the 2- by-4 method. 
  The JAS bans the use of coniferous plywood for a concrete 
mold and strictly restricts the use of North American timber as 
structural wood such as pillars and beams. The letter has 
demanded the review of such restrictions. With regard to the 
Plant Protection Law, it has requested that negotiations on 
import agreements be shortened. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

