<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Submit Position Paper on Nuclear Arms Use </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo To Submit Position Paper on Nuclear Arms Use </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0306063194 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 3 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0306063194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 3 June Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] According to a report submitted by the Ministry of 
Foreign Affairs to the ruling parties' policy committee on 2 
June, the government is considering submitting to the 
International Court of Justice [ICJ] a position paper stating 
that "the use of nuclear arms is not necessarily a violation of 
international law." Many policy committee members opposed this, 
because "even if this may not violate international law, it may 
not be proper for Japan to express such an opinion." The 
committee asked the Foreign Ministry to reconsider. 
  The WHO general meeting in May 1993 passed a resolution to 
seek a judicial opinion from the ICJ on the issue of "whether 
the use of nuclear arms, in view of its effects on health and 
the environment, constitutes a violation of international law." 
ICJ "agreed to take cognizance of the case," and has been 
asking various countries to give their opinions. The 
above-mentioned position paper is to be submitted to ICJ in 
response to this request, which has a deadline of 10 June. 
  According to a briefing given to the policy committee, the 
Foreign Ministry first questions the jurisdiction of ICJ as to 
whether it is appropriate for ICJ to make a judgment on this 
issue. However, it also asserts that "in Japan's opinion, the 
use of nuclear arms is not necessarily a violation of 
international law." 
  The position paper does not even require a cabinet decision. 
The Foreign Ministry says that with regard to this issue, "what 
we can say is that we are presently considering the problem, 
including whether we should submit a position paper." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-28351 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas111__a94025" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-111-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Statement on Nuclear Arms Use Triggers Controversy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Statement on Nuclear Arms Use Triggers Controversy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0506135394 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 5 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0506135394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A "statement on the use of nuclear arms," which the 
government will soon submit to the International Court of 
Justice, is of the opinion that "the use of nuclear arms is not 
necessarily a violation of international law." Questions are 
being asked within the ruling coalition parties about the 
statement because Japan is the only victim of atomic bombs in 
the world and the statement is likely to trigger a controversy. 
  Last year, the World Health Organization (WHO) asked the 
International Court of Justice about whether "the use of nuclear 
weapons is illegal or not under the international law." In 
response, the International Court of Justice has requested each 
nation to submit its statement by 10 June this year. The 
statement in question has been compiled in response to the 
request from the International Court of Justice. The statement, 
which was compiled by the government on 4 June, notes, "The use 
of nuclear weapons does not conform to the humanitarian spirit 
manifested in the international law." The statement, however, 
says, "Speaking from the assessment of the international law, it 
cannot be said that a legal perception has been established in 
the international community that the use of nuclear weapons is 
illegal under the international law." The Foreign Ministry is 
stressing that "there is no change in this government's legal 
view of the statement," (according to Foreign Ministry spokesman 
Terasuke Terada). 
  When the Foreign Ministry briefed secretaries in charge of 
policy affairs of the ruling coalition parties at a 2 June 
meeting on the statement, one secretary after another refuted 
the statement, asking, "From Japan's position of seeking total 
abolishment of nuclear weapons, can it say the use of nuclear 
weapons is not illegal under the international law?" The 
secretaries asked the Foreign Minister to give additional 
briefing on the statement in writing. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-28352 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas111__a94026" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-111-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Disclose Plutonium Stock `Regularly' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo To Disclose Plutonium Stock `Regularly' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0506160294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 4 Jun 94 
Morning Edition p 12 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0506160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mikio Omi, director general of the Science and 
Technology Agency [STA] announced on 3 June a plan to regularly 
disclose the amount of plutonium Japan has in stock. This is a 
part of the measures designed to show at home and abroad the 
transparency of Japan's plutonium utilization, in which other 
countries are interested. He explained this plan in response to 
a question asked by Osamu Imamura (of the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan [SDPJ]) at the House of Representatives Science 
and Technological Committee meeting on the same day. 
  In response to an inquiry by Tadatoshi Akiba, lower house 
Dietman (of the SDPJ), the STA disclosed last October the amount 
of plutonium in stock. However, the agency will make regular 
announcements in the future. Regarding the frequency of and how 
to make the announcements, the STA will study some possibilities 
while taking several factors into consideration, including 
progress at meetings on the framework of international plutonium 
utilization. 
  Director General Omi stressed: "To obtain understanding and 
cooperation from the people, it is important for us to disclose 
as much information as possible, except information on the 
protection of property rights, such as know-how regarding the 
protection of nuclear materials." 
  The amount of plutonium in stock as of late December last 
year, when the same agency made the announcement, was 1,600 
kilograms. Moreover, 2,900 kg of plutonium was stored in Britain 
and France, where plutonium is being reprocessed for Japan. The 
government announced previously that it would continue to 
maintain a balance between the supply of and demand for 
plutonium. Therefore, the government needs to disclose the 
amount of plutonium in stock to actually show that it is abiding 
by its own announcement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

